Git install on Windows

Author

Ed123 Pal

1 Introduction

This tutorial instructs how to install Git on a Windows computer.

After Git is installed, youâll see how to explore whatâs been installed, how to add Git to the PATH environment variable and then do a quick verification that Git is working.

2 Learning Objectives

After completing this tutorial, you should be able to:

  1. Locate and use a website to download a self-extracting Git installation file.

  2. Install the Git software.

  3. Confirm Git is on the Path environment variable.

  4. Check the Git version, verifying that R is working.

3 Download Git Software

3.1 Git website

Go to the Git website.

Click on Download for Windows.

3.2 Start download

Click on the 64-bit Git for Windows Setup (assuming you have a 64-bit computer).

After the download completes, look in the Downloads folder to find the zipped file that contains the self-extracting Git installation file.

Note

The numbers shown on the downloaded file will likely be higher than whatâs seen in the screenshot above because there will likely be a newer version of Git available when you are reading this tutorial.

4 Install Git

4.1 Downloads folder

See the installation file in the Download folder.

4.2 Start install

Double-click on the self-extracting Git installation file to start the installation wizard running.

You may first see a window asking for permission to change your device. If so, click Yes.

5 Verify install

5.1 Path variable

Verify the Git installation process added Git to the Path variable. If not, do so.

5.2 Git version

Open a Command Prompt window and check the Git version. If the Git version command returns the Git version then itâs likely the Git software is working correctly.
